03957nam a22005175i 9780774855242DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072006xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748552427 a10.59962/97807748552422doi  a(DE-B1597)661213  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1745.5bK46 2006eb 7aSOC0480002bisacsh04a305.42095491 aKhan, Shahnaz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aZina, Transnational Feminism, and the Moral Regulation of Pakistani Women /cShahnaz Khan. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (160 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tImportant Dates -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcronyms -- tIntroduction -- tNative Informing on the Zina Ordinance -- tContextualizing the Zina Ordinance -- tSpeaking to the Women -- tDisobedient Daughters, Errant Wives, and Others -- tCurrent Challenges to the Zina Ordinance -- tA Politics of Transnationality and Reconfigured Native Informing -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Zina Ordinance is part of the Hadood Ordinances that were promulgated in 1979 by the military dictator General Zia-ul-Haq, a self-proclaimed president of Pakistan. Since then, tens of thousands of Pakistani women have been charged and incarcerated under the ordinance, which governs illicit sex. Although most of these women are subsequently released for lack of evidence, they spend months or years in jail before trial. To date, these laws still remain in effect, despite international calls for their repeal. Over a five-year-period, Shahnaz Khan interviewed women incarcerated under the zina laws in Pakistan. She argues that the zina laws help situate morality within the individual, thus de-emphasizing the prevalence of societal injustice. She also examines the production and reception of knowledge in the west about women in the third world, identifying a productive tension between living in the west and doing research in the third world. She concludes that transnational feminist solidarity can help women identify the linkages between the local and global and challenge oppressive practices internationally. This analysis will appeal to scholars and students of gender, law, human rights, and Islamic/Middle Eastern studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485524240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774855242423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774855242/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles